Data Description¶

Data is extracted from Booking.com. This dataset contains 515,000 customer reviews and a rating of 1,493 hotels across Europe. The geographical location of hotels is also provided for further analysis.
There are the following columns:

  • Hotel Address
  • Additional_Number_of_Scoring
  • Review_Date
  • Average_Score
  • Hotel_Name
  • Reviewer_Nationality
  • Negative_Review
  • Review_Total_Negative_Word_Counts
  • Total_Number_of_Reviews
  • Positive_Review
  • Review_Total_Positive_Word_Counts
  • Total_Number_of_Reviews_Reviewer_Has_Given
  • Reviewer_Score
  • Tags
  • days_since_review
  • lat
  • lng
  • dtype

Reviewers Origin¶

Let's see where the reviewers come from. Later will investigate the relation between nationality and average score left. Also, to achieve hogher accuracy of analysis, let's cut off countries from where there are less than 50 reviews.

In [6]:
origin = df["Reviewer_Nationality"].value_counts()[df["Reviewer_Nationality"].value_counts() > 50]
dt = df.groupby("Reviewer_Nationality").mean()

Countries, reviewers from where left the highest scores (8 and more):

In [10]:
world = gpd.read_file('data/world-countries.json')

high_map = alt.Chart(world).project(type = 'equalEarth').mark_geoshape(stroke = 'white').encode(
     fill = alt.condition(
        alt.FieldOneOfPredicate('name', high_list),
        alt.value('#9D79FF'),
        alt.value('lightgray')),
    tooltip = [
        alt.Tooltip('name:N')]
).properties(width = 600, height = 500,  title="High Scores come from:")

low_map = alt.Chart(world).project(type = 'equalEarth').mark_geoshape(stroke = 'white').encode(
     fill = alt.condition(
        alt.FieldOneOfPredicate('name', low_list),
        alt.value('#9D79FF'),
        alt.value('lightgray')),
    tooltip = [
        alt.Tooltip('name:N')]
).properties(width = 600, height = 500, title="Low Scores come from:")

alt.hconcat(high_map, 
            low_map
           ).configure_title(fontSize=15, anchor='middle'
           ).properties(background = 'white', padding = 25, title="Origin of the highest and the lowest Scores \n")
Out[10]:

I did not put two types of countries on single map using different colors. On two separate maps the pattern is more clear. As we can see, hotel guests from quite poor countries are tend to leave lower scores, while visitor from most of vell developed countries tend to leave high scores. This pattern is quite interesting because I expected the opposite outcome.

Word Cloud¶

My next step is to analyze the text from both positive and negative reviews and display it as a word clouds.
Below you can see the cloud with the most common words from negative reviews:

In [13]:
text = " ".join(review for review in df['Negative_Review'])

stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
stopwords.update(["Nan","Negative","etc","didn't"])

wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords=stopwords, background_color="white", max_words=100).generate(text)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,10))
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis("off")
plt.show()

After looking at cloud we can assume that most of visitors were not satisfied with their rooms, breakfasts and hotels in general.
Below is the word cloud with positive reviews:

In [12]:
text = " ".join(review for review in df['Positive_Review'])

stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
stopwords.update(["Nan","Negative","etc"])

wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords=stopwords, background_color="white", max_words=100).generate(text)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,10))
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis("off")
plt.show()

From these results we assume that visitors were satisfied with the location of the hotel, rooms and hotel staff.
